Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Peel the @garlic{1%unit}, pop into a small piece of #foil{} with a drizzle of
@oil{to taste}. Scrunch to enclose.

Cut the @tomato{2%unit} into 2cm chunks.

Pop the tomatoes onto a lined #baking tray{}, drizzle with @oil{to taste} and
season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}. Place the garlic parcel
alongside.

Roast on the top shelf until the tomatoes are softened, ~{12-15%minutes}.

Meanwhile, cut the @baguette{2%unit} widthways at an angle into 2cm slices.

Lay the slices onto a separate lined baking tray. Drizzle with @oil{to taste}
and season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}. Toast until golden brown,
~{8-10%minutes}.

Drain and tear the @mozzarella{125%grams} into small chunks.

Once the garlic has roasted, mash with a #fork{}.

Pop the mashed garlic into a #bowl{} with the tomatoes along with any juices
from the tray. Mix to combine.

Layer some of the garlickly roast tomatoes, mozzarella and @salad leaves{40%grams}
onto each of the baguette slices.

Season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}.

Finish with a drizzle of @balsamic glaze{1%sachet}.

> Crunchy baguette slices are topped with garlicky slow-roasted tomato, creamy
> mozzarella and peppery salad leaves to create a pleasing bruschetta antipasto
> that's simply perfetto.